Problem Statement: Concrete Strength Prediction¶

Objective¶

To predict the concrete strength using the data available in file concrete_data.xls. Apply feature engineering and model tuning to obtain 80% to 95% of R2score.

About Dataset and variable¶

Data Type: multivariate

Abstract: Concrete is the most important material in civil engineering. The concrete compressive strength is a highly nonlinear function of age and ingredients. These ingredients include cement, blast furnace slag, fly ash, water, superplasticizer, coarse aggregate, and fine aggregate.

Variable Information:

Given is the variable name, variable type, the measurement unit and a brief description. The concrete compressive strength is the regression problem. The order of this listing corresponds to the order of numerals along the rows of the database.

Name -- Data Type -- Measurement -- Description

Cement (component 1) -- quantitative -- kg in a m3 mixture -- Input Variable

Blast Furnace Slag (component 2) -- quantitative -- kg in a m3 mixture -- Input Variable

Fly Ash (component 3) -- quantitative -- kg in a m3 mixture -- Input Variable

Water (component 4) -- quantitative -- kg in a m3 mixture -- Input Variable

Superplasticizer (component 5) -- quantitative -- kg in a m3 mixture -- Input Variable

Coarse Aggregate (component 6) -- quantitative -- kg in a m3 mixture -- Input Variable

Fine Aggregate (component 7) -- quantitative -- kg in a m3 mixture -- Input Variable

Age -- quantitative -- Day (1~365) -- Input Variable

Concrete compressive strength -- quantitative -- MPa -- Output Variable¶

# Finding outliers using Inter-Quartile Range which difference between 75th and 27th percentiles
# IQR = Q  Q
# https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Interquartile_range
def findOutLiers(data):
    cols =data.columns
    outliersCols=[]
    for col in cols:
        q1 = data[col].quantile(0.25)
        q3 = data[col].quantile(0.75)
        iqr = q3-q1
        lower_range = q1-(1.5*iqr)
        upper_range = q3+(1.5*iqr) 
        isOutlier = (data.loc[(data[col] < lower_range)|(data[col] > upper_range)]).empty
        if isOutlier:
            display(Markdown("There are no outliers in {0}".format(col)))#("There are no outliers in {0}".format(col))
        else:
            print('\033[91m'+ "There are outliers in column - {0}".format(col))
            outliersCols.append(col)

    print("Columns containing outliers are : {0} ".format(outliersCols))

    noOfRows=(int)(len(outliersCols)/2)
    noOfCols=2
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(nrows = noOfRows, ncols = noOfCols, figsize=(15,15))
    colIndex = 0         
    for outlierCol in outliersCols: 
        sns.set()
        sns.boxplot(data[outlierCol], ax = axs[math.floor(colIndex/noOfCols)][colIndex % noOfCols])
        colIndex += 1 
    return outliersCols

    pos=1
    for i in data.drop(targetColumn, axis=1).columns:

for col in col_outliters:
        q1,q2,q3 = dfConcreteLeanData[col].quantile([0.25, 0.5,0.75])
        IQR = q3-q1
        a = dfConcreteLeanData[col]>q3+1.5*IQR
        b = dfConcreteLeanData[col]<q1-1.5*IQR
        dfConcreteLeanData[col]=np.where(a|b, q2, dfConcreteLeanData[col])

target = "strength"
def model(model,dtrainx,dtrainy,dtestx,dtesty,of_type, algorithm_name):
    
    print (model)
    print ("\n")
    model.fit(dtrainx,dtrainy)
    prediction = model.predict(dtestx)
    score_train = model.score(dtrainx, dtrainy)
    score_test = model.score(dtestx, dtesty)
    print("score_train", score_train)
    print("score_test", score_test)
    print ("ROOT MEAN SQUARED ERROR :", np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(dtesty,prediction)) )
    print ("\n")
    prediction = pd.DataFrame(prediction)
    cross_val = cross_val_score(model,dtrainx,dtrainy,cv=20,scoring="neg_mean_squared_error")
    cross_val = cross_val.ravel()
    result = pd.DataFrame({'Model' : [algorithm_name], 'score_train': score_train*100,'score_test':score_test*100,'cv-std' : [cross_val.std()],
                           'RMSE' : [ np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(dtesty,prediction))]})
    
    return result
